{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"649cb835-1cf2-4774-9786-c001b2d2b75c","content":"## What changed\n\nC# 14 extends **first-class span support**, which changes **overload resolution** for arrays. When you call `array.Contains(num)` on an `int[]`, the compiler now prefers:\n\n```\nMemoryExtensions.Contains<T>(this ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)\n```\n\nover the old:\n\n```\nEnumerable.Contains<T>(this IEnumerable<T>, T)\n```\n\nbecause the implicit `T[]` → `ReadOnlySpan<T>` conversion is ranked as more specific than `T[]` → `IEnumerable<T>`. Since `ReadOnlySpan<T>` is a **ref struct**, it cannot be represented in expression trees — so the expression tree compiler/interpreter blows up.\n\n## How to fix\n\nForce the compiler to resolve to `Enumerable.Contains` by disambiguating:\n\n**Option A — cast the array to `IEnumerable<int>`:**\n```csharp\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);\n```\n\n**Option B — call `Enumerable.Contains` explicitly:**\n```csharp\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);\n```\n\nBoth remove the span conversion from the picture so the expression tree only references types it can represent.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"74552392-63a2-4b27-b3e3-5107eccd15cc","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a breaking change in .NET 10 / C# 14 that affects LINQ expression trees calling `.Contains()` on `int[]` arrays.\n\nLet me think about what changed in .NET 10 / C# 14 that would cause this.\n\nIn C# 14, there's a significant change related to extension members. C# 14 introduces a new \"extension\" feature. But more relevantly, there's a breaking change related to how the compiler resolves `Contains` on arrays.\n\nThe key issue: In C# 13 and earlier, `array.Contains(num)` where `array` is `int[]` would resolve to `System.Linq.Enumerable.Contains<int>(IEnumerable<int>, int)` — the LINQ extension method from `System.Linq`.\n\n\nIn .NET 9, `MemoryExtensions` added overloads for `Contains` on `Span<T>` and `ReadOnlySpan<T>`, and since arrays implicitly convert to these types, the compiler in .NET 10 / C# 14 now prefers the `MemoryExtensions.Contains` method over the LINQ version. This preference shift is causing the breaking change in expression trees.\n\nThe problem is that `MemoryExtensions.Contains` works with spans, which are ref structs and can't be represented in expression trees. So when the compiler resolves `array.Contains(item)` to the span-based overload instead of the LINQ enumerable version, it breaks any code trying to use this in an expression tree context. tree interpreter can't handle ref struct types like `ReadOnlySpan<T>`, so if the compiler resolved `Contains` to `MemoryExtensions.Contains` in C# 14, the expression tree would fail at runtime. But wait—expression trees shouldn't even allow ref struct types at compile time, so that doesn't quite fit. Let me think about whether there's a new overload resolution issue, maybe from the params collections feature adding `params ReadOnlySpan<T>` variants. the expression tree is being constructed through lambda syntax, which the compiler transforms into expression tree construction calls. If C# 14 is resolving `array.Contains(num)` to the `MemoryExtensions` overload that uses `ReadOnlySpan<T>`, the compiler should reject this at compile time since expression trees can't contain ref struct operations. So this should be a compile-time error, not a runtime issue. But maybe something else changed in how the resolution works.\n\nI'm wondering if the real culprit is that .NET 10 or C# 14 altered overload resolution for arrays, possibly preferring span-based methods from `MemoryExtensions` over the traditional `Enumerable.Contains`, or if there's a new interface implementation on arrays that's affecting method selection. `.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)` instead, since span conversions are now preferred in C# 13+. But expression trees should reject this conversion—unless there's a compiler bug or it falls back to `Enumerable` in that context. If the tree does compile with `Enumerable.Contains`, it should work fine at runtime with `preferInterpretation: true`, unless .NET 10 changed how `Enumerable.Contains` handles arrays internally in a way the interpreter can't handle.\n\nActually, I'm wondering if this is related to broader changes in C# 13 or .NET 9 around how method resolution works for things like `string.Contains(char)`. Maybe the compiler is now resolving `Contains` on arrays differently, and that's what's causing the issue in .NET 10.\n\nThe most likely culprit seems to be C# 14's improved span support changing how overload resolution works. If `array.Contains(num)` now resolves to the `MemoryExtensions.Contains` method that takes a `ReadOnlySpan<T>` instead of the LINQ `Enumerable.Contains`, that would explain the problem—since ref structs can't be used in expression trees. In a regular lambda this would fail at compile time, but something different might be happening here. onsider what's actually happening here. The user says it throws at runtime, so maybe the compiler does pick `Enumerable.Contains` instead of the span-based method when building the expression tree, avoiding the CS8640 error, but then something breaks at runtime in .NET 10. Or perhaps the expression tree is being constructed programmatically rather than through the compiler's lambda conversion. Let me look at the user's code again to understand what's really going on. I think the real issue is that C# 14's overload resolution has changed how `Contains` is resolved on arrays. With the refined span conversion rules in .NET 10, `array.Contains(num)` now resolves to `MemoryExtensions.Contains<T>` which takes a `ReadOnlySpan<T>`, and this span-based implementation might not be compatible with expression tree interpretation or has different behavior that causes the runtime error. the compiler now prefer